{
  "text": "Flow cytometry may provide an alternative means of detecting activity or substrate uptake in single microbial cells. It allows the physical sorting of particular bacterial populations of interest for further analyses [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . So far, microbial cells from plankton samples have been mainly sorted by phenotypic features, e.g., cell volume or cellular DNA or protein content [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Sorted bacteria have been analyzed by molecular methods [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] and for radiotracer incorporation [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] . In contrast to microautoradiography, the tracer uptake rates of specific cell populations can be readily quantified by this approach.",
  "correct_citation": {
